[[File:Exvoto bastetano de bronce (M.A.N. 18538) 01.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Bronze]] [[votive]] feminine figure of the Bastetani]] [[File:Bastetania en las provincias actuales del SE español.svg|thumb|Territory of the Bastetani]] The '''Bastetani''' or '''Bastuli''' were an [[Iberians|ancient Iberian]] (pre-[[Ancient Rome|Roman]]) people of the [[Iberian peninsula]] (the Roman [[Hispania]]). They are believed to have spoken the [[Iberian language]].
Their territory extended through present-day the south part of [[Albacete Province|Albacete]], [[Almería Province|Almería]], [[Granada Province|Granada]], the eastern part of [[Málaga Province|Málaga]], and the southeastern part of [[Province of Jaén (Spain)|Jaén]], as well as the western part of the [[Murcia Region]] in the southeastern region of the [[Iberian Peninsula]]. Their main towns were from ''Baria'', present-day [[Cuevas del Almanzora|Villaricos]], to ''Bailo'' ([[Cádiz Province|Cádiz]]), as well as ''[[History of Málaga|Malaka]]'', ''Abdera'', ''Sexi'' and ''Carteia''.<ref>Luis A. García Moreno, ''Mastienos y Bastetanos: un problema de la etnología hispana prerromana.'' 1990</ref>
==See also== *[[Iberians]] *[[Pre-Roman peoples of the Iberian Peninsula]] *[[Lady of Baza]]
== References == {{reflist}}
==External links== {{Commons category|Bastetani}} *[https://web.archive.org/web/20040611215344/http://www.arqueotavira.com/Mapas/Iberia/Populi.htm Detailed map of the Pre-Roman Peoples of Iberia (around 200 BC)]
{{Pre-Roman peoples in Spain}}
