{{europe-ethno-group-stub}} {{Spain-hist-stub}}

The '''Bergistani''' ({{lang-la|Bargusi}}), were an ancient [[Iberians|Iberian]] or [[Ancient Rome|Pre-Roman]] people of the [[Iberian peninsula]]. They were related to the [[Ilergetes]] and were not numerous. They inhabited the valley of the Saiarra river in the upper course of the [[Llobregat]] in the northern [[Tarraconense]].
The Bergistani were defeated by [[Hannibal]] during his overland journey to [[Italy]]. They are also known for having rebelled against Rome in 197 BC. The rebellion was put down by consul [[Cato the Elder]].<ref>{{citation |last=Martínez Gázquez |first=José |work=La campaña de Catón en Hispania |chapter= |url=https://books.google.cat/books?id=JUGTz_7YXDAC&pg=PA172&dq=197+ac+hispania&lr=&client=firefox-a&hl=ca&cd=1#v=onepage&q=197%20ac%20hispania&f=false|language=Spanish |edition=First|publisher=Publicacions i Edicions UB |isbn=9788478759804 |date=1992 |ref =}}</ref> When they rose in revolt for the second time they were reduced to [[slavery]]. [[Livy]] mentions that the Bergistani had seven castles or fortifications. Their main castle, ''Castrum Bergium'', could correspond to present-day [[Berga]].
==See also== *[[Pre-Roman peoples of the Iberian Peninsula]]
