{{Politics of Ecuador}}
A referendum on banning politicians and civil servants from having bank accounts or companies based in [[tax havens]] was held in [[Ecuador]] on 19 February 2017, alongside [[Ecuadorian general election, 2017|general elections]].<ref>[http://www.ecuadortimes.net/2016/11/22/referendum-on-tax-havens-will-be-conducted-in-the-elections-of-2017/ Referendum on tax havens will be conducted in the elections of 2017] Ecuador Times, 22 November 2016</ref> The proposal was approved by voters, giving officials one year to transfer their assets.<ref name=TS/> If they do not, they will be removed from their posts.<ref name=TS/>
The question on the ballot was "Do you agree that, for those holding a popularly elected office or for public servants, there should be a prohibition on holding assets or capital, of any nature, in tax havens?"<ref name=TS/>
==Classification of tax havens== In preparation for the referendum, the Ecuadorian Internal Revenue Service issued a resolution outlining the criteria for a jurisdiction to be considered a tax haven, establishing two categories: Preferential tax regimes, and low tax jurisdictions.<ref name=EY>[http://www.ey.com/gl/en/services/tax/international-tax/alert--ecuadorian-irs-issues-resolution-with-new-list-of-tax-haven-jurisdictions Ecuadorian IRS issues resolution with new list of tax haven jurisdictions] EY, 9 February 2015</ref> A preferential tax regime was classed as a jurisdiction whose effective tax rate is below 60% in relation to the Ecuadorian corporate income tax (CIT) rate of 13.2%.<ref name=EY/> A low tax jurisdiction was classed as having an effective tax rate below 60% in relation to the Ecuadorian CIT of 13.2% and no substantial economic activity.<ref name=EY/> The IRS may remove a country from their list of tax havens if it reforms its tax policy, if it enforces a treaty to avoid double taxation, including a special information exchange clause, or if its laws do not include banking confidentiality, securities or other regulations that prohibit sharing information with the Ecuadorian IRS.<ref name=EY/>
Along with this definition, the Ecuadorian IRS published a list of countries which currently meet the definition of a tax haven under their law.<ref name=EY/> This list included 28 jurisdictions in the Americas, 19 in Oceania, 16 in Europe, 13 in Asia, 9 in Africa and two other island territories.
{| |valign=top|'''Africa''' *[[Angola]] *[[Cape Verde]] *[[Djibouti]] *[[Liberia]] *[[Mauritius]] *[[Nigeria]] *[[Seychelles]] *[[Swaziland]] *[[Tunisia]] |valign=top|'''Americas''' *[[American Samoa]] *[[Anguilla]]{{efn|name=fn1|[[United Kingdom|British]] Overseas Territory}} *[[Antigua and Barbuda]] *[[Aruba]]{{efn|name=fn2|Part of the Kingdom of the Netherlands}} *[[Bahamas]] *[[Barbados]] *[[Belize]] *[[Bermuda]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[Bonaire]]{{efn|name=fn2}} *[[British Virgin Islands]] *[[Cayman Islands]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[Cocos Island]] (Costa Rica) *[[Curacao]]{{efn|name=fn2|Part of the Kingdom of the Netherlands}} *[[Dominica]] *[[Greenland]] *[[Grenada]] *[[Guyana]] *[[Montserrat]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[Panama]] *[[Puerto Rico]]{{efn|name=fn3|[[United States]] unincorporated territory}} *[[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] *[[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]{{efn|name=fn4|Overseas Collectivity of [[France]]}} *[[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] *[[Saint Martin]] *[[Saint Helena]] *[[Santa Lucia]] *[[Trinidad and Tobago]] *[[Turks and Caicos Islands]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[United States Virgin Islands]] |valign=top|'''Asia''' *[[Bahrain]] *[[Brunei Darussalam]] *[[Jordan]] *[[Kuwait]] *[[Labuan]] ([[Malaysia]]) *[[Macau]] *[[Maldives]] *[[Myanmar]] *[[Oman]] *[[Qeshm]] ([[Iran]]) *[[Sri Lanka]] *[[United Arab Emirates]] *[[Yemen]] |valign=top|'''Europe''' *[[Albania]] *[[Andorra]] *[[Azores Islands]] ([[Portugal]]) *[[Campione d'Italia]] ([[Italy]]) *[[Channel Islands]]{{efn|name=fn5|British Dependency}} *[[Cyprus]] *[[Gibraltar]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[Isle of Man]]{{efn|name=fn5}} *[[Liechtenstein]] *[[Luxembourg]] *[[Madeira]] (Portugal) *[[Malta]] *[[Monaco]] *[[Ostrava|Ostrava Free Zone]] ([[Czech Republic]]) *[[San Marino]] *[[Svalbard]] ([[Norway]]) *[[Trieste]] (Italy) |valign=top|'''Oceania''' *[[Christmas Island]]{{efn|name=fn6|[[Australia|Australian]] External Territory}} *[[Cook Islands]]{{efn|name=fn7|Free Association with [[New Zealand]]}} *[[French Polynesia]]{{efn|name=fn4}} *[[Guam]]{{efn|name=fn3}} *[[Kiribati]] *[[Marshall Islands]] *[[Nauru]] *[[Niue]]{{efn|name=fn7}} *[[Norfolk Island]] (Australia) *[[Palau]]{{efn|Free Association with the United States}} *[[Pitcairn Islands]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[Samoa]] *[[Solomon Islands]] *[[Tokelau]]{{efn|Dependent territory of New Zealand}} *[[Tonga]] *[[Tuvalu]] *[[Vanuatu]] |valign=top|'''Other''' *[[Ascension Island]]{{efn|name=fn1}} *[[Tristan da Cunha]]{{efn|name=fn1}} |}
==Campaign== Outgoing President [[Rafael Correa]] stated that he would campaign in favour of the proposal,<ref name=TS>[http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Ecuador-to-Hold-Referendum-on-Tax-Havens-20161123-0016.html Ecuador to Hold Referendum on Tax Havens] Telesur, 23 November 2016</ref> having previously stated that tax havens were one of the biggest issues for democracy.<ref>[http://www.andes.info.ec/en/news/president-correa-tax-havens-are-one-biggest-problems-our-democracies.html President Correa: tax havens are one of the biggest problems in our democracies] Andes, 29 July 2016</ref>
