{{Infobox building | name = Vaduz Castle | native_name = Schloss Vaduz {{de icon}} | image = Schlossvaduz.jpg | map_type = Liechtenstein | altitude = | building_type = [[Palace]] | ren_cost = | location = [[Vaduz]], [[Liechtenstein]] | address = | client = | owner = [[Princely Family of Liechtenstein]] | coordinates = {{coord|47|08|22|N|9|31|28|E|region:LI|display=inline,title}} | start_date = 12th century | height = | diameter = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = }}
'''Vaduz Castle''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Schloss Vaduz'') is the [[palace]] and [[official residence]] of the [[Prince of Liechtenstein]].<ref name=o>{{cite web|url=http://www.gowealthy.com/gowealthy/wcms/en/home/articles/travel/sightseeing/Vaduz-Castle-Liechtenstein-JPhKgKrA1x.html |title=Sightseeing : Vaduz Castle- Liechtenstein |publisher=Gowealthy.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref> The castle gave its name to the town of [[Vaduz]], the capital of [[Liechtenstein]], which it overlooks from an adjacent hilltop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virtualtourist.com/travel/Europe/Liechtenstein/Vaduz/Things_To_Do-Vaduz-MISC-BR-1.html |title=Fun Things To Do in Vaduz - Attractions & Must See |publisher=VirtualTourist |date= |accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tourismus.li/en/lie/place/Vaduz%20Castle/ |title=Principality of Liechtenstein: Travel, holidays, vacations - Activities - Popular sights & the countryside: Vaduz Castle |date=31 March 2018 |accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>
==History== The former owners, who were presumably also the builders, were the counts of [[County of Sargans|Werdenberg-Sargans]]. The [[bergfried]] (the [[keep]], built in the 12th century) and parts of the eastern side are the oldest. The tower stands on a piece of ground that is {{convert|12|x|13|m|0|abbr=off}} in area. At the ground floor, the tower walls have a thickness of up to {{convert|4|m|0|abbr=off}}. The original entrance lay at the courtyard side at a height of {{convert|11|m|0|abbr=off}}. The chapel of St. Anna was presumably built in the [[Middle Ages]] as well. The main altar is late-gothic. In the [[Swabian War]] of 1499, the castle was burned by the [[Old Swiss Confederacy|Swiss Confederacy]]. The western side was expanded by Count Kaspar von Hohenems (1613–1640).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tourismus.li/en/culture-cuisine/places-of-cultural-interest/cultural-places-of-historical-interest/Vaduz-Castle.html |title=Liechtenstein : The Official Tourism Site - Culture & Cuisine - Places of historical interest : Vaduz Castle |date=2013-01-05 |accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Cornelia Herrmann |chapter=Die Kunstdenkmäler des Fürstentums Liechtenstein. Das Oberland|title=Gesellschaft für Schweizerische Kunstgeschichte GSK: ''Die Kunstdenkmäler der Schweiz''|location=Bern|year=2007|isbn=978-3-906131-85-6 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burgenwelt.org/liechtenstein/vaduz/object.php |title=Vaduz Castle on Burgenwelt.de (in German) |date=2016-01-22 |accessdate=2016-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burgenwelt.org/liechtenstein/vaduz/object.php#grundriss |title=Ground plan of Vaduz Castle on Burgenwelt.de (in German) |date=2016-01-22 |accessdate=2016-01-22}}</ref>
The [[Princely Family of Liechtenstein]] acquired Vaduz Castle in 1712 when it purchased the countship of Vaduz. At this time, [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor]], combined the countship with the Lordship of [[Schellenberg]], purchased by the Liechtensteins in 1699, to form the present Principality of Liechtenstein.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schloss Vaduz, Liechtenstein|url=http://www.galenfrysinger.com/liechtenstein_schloss_vaduz.htm|author=Galen R Frysinger, Sheboygan, Wisconsin|accessdate=22 July 2009}}</ref>
==Today== The castle underwent a major restoration between 1904 and 1920, then again in the early 1920s during the reign of [[Johann II, Prince of Liechtenstein|Prince Johann II]], and was expanded during the early 1930s by [[Franz Joseph II, Prince of Liechtenstein|Prince Franz Joseph II]]. Since 1938, the castle has been the primary residence of Liechtenstein's Princely Family. The castle is not open to the public as the princely family still lives in the castle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://merlinandrebecca.blogspot.com/2011/08/castle-hunting-schloss-valduz.html |title=Article about Vaduz Castle and Schalun castle (includes images of both) |date=2011-08-18 |accessdate=2013-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tourismus.li/en/culture-cuisine/places-of-cultural-interest/cultural-places-of-historical-interest/Vaduz-Castle.html |title=Liechtenstein - Vaduz Castle |publisher=Tourismus.li |date= |accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruinenland.de/burgen-luxemburg.htm |title=Photo gallery of Liechtenstein and Luxembourg castles, including photos of Vaduz Castle |date=2011-08-18 |accessdate=2013-04-14}}</ref>
